Unlike past national days when the President mostly dwelt on the government’s performance scorecard, yesterday’s address was largely on the BBI, what he called the First Amendment. The President pushed the need for a referendum, shutting the door on any amendments.
He also answered critics of the proposed changes, noting that “the making of a nation is not a destination, it’s a journey… and our founding fathers taught us this, by example.”





Deputy President William Ruto has been pushing for amendments where the role of women leaders would be reverted to the National Assembly and that there be multiple questions at the referendum.
The President said women leaders would be of much help at the Senate as proposed.
Expanded executive
The President said the 2007/08 post-election violence brought in an expanded executive and it is time this was made permanent.
“Our national spirit had been wounded and we were afraid of repeating the 2007 post-election violence. But, in running away from one crisis, we created another. And, now is the moment to correct this and make a shift from a constitution of fear to a constitution of hope, a constitution that ensures our nation remains stable; and therefore, attractive to both local and foreign investors,” said the Head of State.



