 He said the envisaged changes will cure the violence that visits Kenyans every five years during elections.
“If it takes an absurd 123 days to conduct an election or one-third of a year, like we did in 2017, this is a sign that the moment calls for change. If the country loses Sh1 trillion during these 123 days of an election, or an equivalent of one-third of our national budget, this is a sign that a moment of reckoning is approaching,” he said.
“And, if every five years we lose life and property, including our young ones, this a pointer to constitutional decay. It is a sign that the letter of our constitution has become rigid and is not in tandem with the deep-seated aspirations of our people.”
Constitutional questions
The President was categorical that BBI is not a “one-size-fits-all” that promises to settle all the constitutional questions through a singular amendment, but a starting point to a continuous process of constitution-making.
He said in an expanded executive, a nation as ethnically diverse as Kenya does not augur well for nationhood to have just two occupants at the apex of the Executive – the President and the Deputy President.
He noted the Kofi Annan consensus of February 2008, which ushered in the grand coalition government, succeeded because of an expanded executive.



