“Five positions at the apex of the Executive means that some people will be left out. This is why BBI proposes to re-introduce the position of Leader of Official Opposition that was so successful under the former constitutional order. An expanded Executive and constitutional recognition of the opposition will reduce the notion of ‘political scarcity’ and the propensity for electoral violence every five years,” he stated.
On devolution, the President noted that through increasing funds to counties by the national government from 15 per cent to 35 per cent, more money to the counties would mean more money to the people.
He added that creating a ward development fund will take development as close to the people as possible.
Well aware that the case of women parliamentarians being in the Senate is an issue that has caused a ruckus even from his deputy, who has termed it as tokenism, the President said women “will control half the Senate decisions”.
Strengthening devolution
“Devolution without women is like a seedless field where nothing grows. And, this is why we must ask the following question here: Who loses if women control 50 per cent of the Senate, its resources and its decisions? Is strengthening devolution through a 50:50 co-creation formula between men and women good for country? Does this formula support a constitution of fear or does it create a constitution of hope?” posed the President.



